5000|$|The {{pectoral}} fins on most fish control pitching (up-and-down {{motion of}} the body), yawing (the side-to-side motion), and rolling. Most hammerhead sharks do not yaw or roll and achieve pitch using their cephalofoils. The smaller cephalofoil of a <b>bonnethead</b> shark is not as successful, {{so they have to}} rely on the combination of cephalofoils and their large pectoral fins for most of their motility. Compared to other hammerheads, <b>bonnethead</b> sharks have larger and more developed pectoral fins and are the only species of hammerhead to actively use pectoral fins for swimming.|$|E
50|$|A <b>bonnethead</b> female {{produced}} a pup by parthenogenesis. The birth {{took place at}} the Henry Doorly Zoo in Nebraska and subsequent DNA analysis has shown a perfect match between mother and pup.|$|E
